{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_289c4bb43ffeh1fAUGyexNPYoK","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d763b59580015wWuNtVtTddMlI","parts":[{"id":"prt_d763b6610001JVNfV1QdmC1UOV","messageID":"msg_d763b59580015wWuNtVtTddMlI","sessionID":"ses_289c4bb43ffeh1fAUGyexNPYoK","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_68a14fcf510848cc93945c2e","state":{"status":"running","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.dev.md"},"time":{"start":1775805097851}}}]}
{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_289c4bb43ffeh1fAUGyexNPYoK","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d763b59580015wWuNtVtTddMlI","parts":[{"id":"prt_d763b6610001JVNfV1QdmC1UOV","messageID":"msg_d763b59580015wWuNtVtTddMlI","sessionID":"ses_289c4bb43ffeh1fAUGyexNPYoK","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_68a14fcf510848cc93945c2e","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.dev.md"},"output":"<path>/workspace/README.dev.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # `neurogym` developer documentation\n2: \n3: Table of Contents\n4: \n5: <!-- This table is automatically kept up to date using the \"Markdown All in One\" extension -->\n6: \n7: - [IDE Settings](#ide-settings)\n8: - [Package Setup](#package-setup)\n9: - [Running the Tests](#running-the-tests)\n10:   - [Test Coverage](#test-coverage)\n11: - [Style Conventions](#style-conventions)\n12:   - [Automated Style Adherence (for VScode users)](#automated-style-adherence-for-vscode-users)\n13:   - [Linting and Formatting (python files)](#linting-and-formatting-python-files)\n14:   - [Spell Check](#spell-check)\n15:   - [Docstrings](#docstrings)\n16:   - [Static Typing](#static-typing)\n17:   - [Formatting Non-python Files](#formatting-non-python-files)\n18:   - [Jupyter Notebooks](#jupyter-notebooks)\n19: - [User Documentation](#user-documentation)\n20:   - [Publishing the Docs](#publishing-the-docs)\n21: - [Versioning](#versioning)\n22: - [Branching Workflow](#branching-workflow)\n23: - [Development Conventions](#development-conventions)\n24: - [Quality Control Workflows](#quality-control-workflows)\n25:   - [Build](#build)\n26:     - [Build-minimal](#build-minimal)\n27:   - [CFF Convert](#cff-convert)\n28:   - [Docs Test](#docs-test)\n29:   - [Hyperlinks](#hyperlinks)\n30:   - [Linting](#linting)\n31:   - [Notebooks](#notebooks)\n32:   - [Code Quality](#code-quality)\n33:   - [Spell Check](#spell-check-1)\n34:   - [Static Typing](#static-typing-1)\n35: - [Making a Release](#making-a-release)\n36:   - [Automated Release Workflow](#automated-release-workflow)\n37:     - [Updating the Token](#updating-the-token)\n38:   - [Manually Creating a Release](#manually-creating-a-release)\n39: \n40: If you're looking for user documentation, go [here](README.md).\n41: \n42: ## IDE Settings\n43: \n44: We use [Visual Studio Code (VS Code)](https://code.visualstudio.com/) as code editor, which we have set up with some\n45: default [settings](.vscode/settings.json) for formatting. We recommend developers to use VS code with the [recommended\n46: extensions](.vscode/extensions.json) to automatically format and check your code upon saving.\n47: \n48: See [VS Code's settings guide](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/getstarted/settings) for more info.\n49: \n50: If using a different IDE, we recommend creating a similar settings file. Feel free to recommend adding this to package\n51: using via a [pull request](#development-conventions).\n52: \n53: ## Package Setup\n54: \n55: See installation instructions of the main [README](README.md#installation), but replace the last command by\n56: \n57: ```bash\n58: pip install -e .'[rl,dev]'\n59: ```\n60: \n61: Note: you can also run this command after completing the \"normal\" installation instructions from the [README](README.md#installation).\n62: \n63: **NOTE for Linux/WSL users:** If you do not have access to a CUDA-capable NVIDIA GPU (which is the case for most users),\n64: above line will install up to 1.5GB of unnecessary GPU libraries. To avoid excessive overhead, we recommend first\n65: installing the CPU-only version of [PyTorch](https://pytorch.org/get-started/locally/):\n66: \n67: ```bash\n68: pip install torch --index-url https://download.pytorch.org/whl/cpu\n69: pip install neurogym[rl,dev]\n70: ```\n71: \n72: ## Running the Tests\n73: \n74: You can check that all components were installed correctly, by running [pytest](https://docs.pytest.org/en/stable/#) from your terminal:\n75: \n76: ```bash\n77: pytest -v\n78: ```\n79: \n80: ### Test Coverage\n81: \n82: In addition to just running the tests to see if they pass, they can be used for coverage statistics, i.e. to determine\n83: how much of the package's code is actually executed during tests. To see the\n84: [coverage](https://pytest-cov.readthedocs.io/en/latest/) results in your terminal, run the following in an activated\n85: conda environment with the dev tools installed:\n86: \n87: ```bash\n88: coverage run -m pytest\n89: coverage report\n90: ```\n91: \n92: `coverage` can also generate output in HTML and other formats; see `coverage help` for more information.\n93: \n94: ## Style Conventions\n95: \n96: ### Automated Style Adherence (for VScode users)\n97: \n98: If you are using VS code, we recommend installing the [recommended extensions](.vscode/extensions.json): in the Extensions tab, type\n99: `@recommended` and then in the \"Workspace Recommendations\" list, click the install button. Make sure these extensions\n100: are activated.\n101: \n102: This way, the IDE will flag and/or auto-fix upon save most violations to our conventions.\n103: \n104: ### Linting and Formatting (python files)\n105: \n106: We use [ruff](https://docs.astral.sh/ruff/) for linting, sorting imports and formatting of python (notebook) files. The\n107: configurations of `ruff` are set [here](.ruff.toml).\n108: \n109: Please ensure both linting (`ruff check .`) and formatting (`ruff format .`) rules are adhered to before requesting a review.\n110: \n111: ### Spell Check\n112: \n113: Please check for common typos by running `typos` or auto-fix typos by running `typos -w` from the command line. Any\n114: false positives you encounter can be added to the ignore list in [pyproject.toml](pyproject.toml) under `tool.typos`.\n115: Note that this tool has a very low false positive rate and therefore misses many spelling errors. Don't assume\n116: everything is correct, just because this check passes.\n117: \n118: ### Docstrings\n119: \n120: Docstrings should be formatted according to the [google docstring\n121: convention](https://sphinxcontrib-napoleon.readthedocs.io/en/latest/example_google.html).\n122: \n123: These conventions are also checked by our linter: `ruff check .`\n124: \n125: ### Static Typing\n126: \n127: We use [inline type annotation](https://typing.readthedocs.io/en/latest/source/libraries.html#how-to-provide-type-annotations) for static typing rather than stub files (i.e. `.pyi` files).\n128: \n129: Since Python 3.11 is used as dev environment and NeuroGym must support Python version ≥3.10, you may see various typing issues at runtime. Here is [a guide to solve the potential runtime issues](https://mypy.readthedocs.io/en/stable/runtime_troubles.html).\n130: \n131: We use [Mypy](http://mypy-lang.org/) as static type checker and the configurations are set in [pyproject.toml](pyproject.toml) file.\n132: \n133: For more info about static typing and mypy, see:\n134: \n135: - [Static typing with Python](https://typing.readthedocs.io/en/latest/index.html#)\n136: - [Mypy doc](https://mypy.readthedocs.io/en/stable/)\n137: \n138: You can run `mypy .` to check for static typing violations before requesting a review.\n139: \n140: ### Formatting Non-python Files\n141: \n142: We use [prettier](https://prettier.io/) for formatting most non-python files.\n143: \n144: You can run `npx prettier --check .` to check the formatting of, or `npx prettier --write .` to auto-format non-python files.\n145: \n146: ### Jupyter Notebooks\n147: \n148: Note that Jupyter notebooks are under much less strict style/linting control than normal python modules. This is on\n149: purpose, as these generally serve as tutorials, in which it is often preferable to \"break\" style conventions for the\n150: sake of making ones point clearer.\n151: \n152: All notebooks (under the docs/ folder) are continuously monitored against breaking by the [notebooks\n153: workflow](#notebooks). For this reason, please keep the default values for e.g. epochs, training cycles, etc low so to\n154: speed this process up. Add a comment to users asking users to increase them if they actually want to the notebook\n155: productively.\n156: \n157: Also, Jupyter notebooks are notoriously difficult to review effectively. To make this slightly easier, please clear the\n158: run history of any (changes to) Jupyter notebooks before committing or merging them. This significantly\n159: improves the reviewability and avoids excessive clutter in the commit history.\n160: \n161: Do this by:\n162: \n163: 1. clearing all outputs to remove from the notebook, and\n164: 2. restarting the kernel (\"restart\" button) to reset which will the `execution_count` of all cells.\n165: \n166: ## User Documentation\n167: \n168: We use [MkDocs](https://www.mkdocs.org/) and its theme [Material for MkDocs](https://squidfunk.github.io/mkdocs-material/) to generate documentations. The configurations of MkDocs are set in [mkdocs.yml](mkdocs.yml) file.\n169: \n170: To watch the changes of current doc in real time, run:\n171: \n172: ```shell\n173: mkdocs serve\n174: ```\n175: \n176: or to watch src and docs directories\n177: \n178: ```shell\n179: mkdocs serve -w docs -w src\n180: ```\n181: \n182: Then open your browser and go to [http://127.0.0.1:8000/](http://127.0.0.1:8000/).\n183: \n184: ### Publishing the Docs\n185: \n186: The docs are published on GitHub pages. We use [mike](https://github.com/jimporter/mike) to deploy the docs to the `gh-pages` branch and to manage the versions of docs.\n187: \n188: Docs are automatically deployed upon each new release to PyPi as part of our [PyPi\n189: release](.github/workflows/release_pypi.yml) workflow and named identically to the newest GitHub version number (i.e. `vX.Y.Z`).\n190: \n191: To manually deploy (additional) versions of the docs, run:\n192: \n193: ```shell\n194: mike deploy -p -u <docs_version_name>\n195: ```\n196: \n197: Add `latest` to the end of the command above, to make this the latest default version of the docs (i.e. the landing page\n198: of https://neurogym.github.io/).\n199: \n200: To remove a given version of the documentation, run\n201: \n202: ```shell\n203: mike delete <docs_version_name>\n204: ```\n205: \n206: Note that all mike operations above will be recorded as git commits to the `gh-pages` branch.\n207: \n208: Use `mike serve` to review all versions of the site that have been committed to the `gh-pages` branch. It’s part of the `mike` tool, which manages versioned documentation for `mkdocs`. This command is best for verifying the production website as it exists in the repository.\n209: \n210: If you have uncommitted changes that you want to preview, use `mkdocs serve` instead of `mike serve`. This will allow you to view your changes locally without committing them first.\n211: \n212: ## Versioning\n213: \n214: We adhere to [semantic versioning](https://semver.org/) standards. In brief this means using `X.Y.Z` versioning, where\n215: \n216: - X = `major` version: representing API-incompatible changes from the previous version\n217: - Y = `minor` version: representing added functionality that is backwards compatible to previous versions\n218: - Z = `patch` version: representing backward compatible bug fixes were made of previous version\n219: \n220: Bumping the version consistently is done using [bump-my-version](https://callowayproject.github.io/bump-my-version/),\n221: which automatically updates all mentions of the current version throughout the package, as defined in the tool's\n222: [settings](.bumpversion.toml). Use `major`, `minor`, or `patch` as the version level in the following command to update\n223: the version:\n224: \n225: ```bash\n226: bump-my-version bump <version level>\n227: ```\n228: \n229: ## Branching Workflow\n230: \n231: We use a [Git Flow](https://nvie.com/posts/a-successful-git-branching-model/)-inspired branching workflow for development. DeepRank2's repository is based on two main branches with infinite lifetime:\n232: \n233: - `main` — this branch contains production (stable) code. All development code is merged into `main` in sometime.\n234: - `dev` — this branch contains pre-production code. When the features are finished then they are merged into `dev`.\n235: \n236: During the development cycle, three main supporting branches are used:\n237: \n238: - Feature branches - Branches that branch off from `dev` and must merge into `dev`: used to develop new features for the upcoming releases.\n239: - Hotfix branches - Branches that branch off from `main` and must merge into `main` and `dev`: necessary to act immediately upon an undesired status of `main`.\n240: - Release branches - Branches that branch off from `dev` and must merge into `main` and `dev`: support preparation of a new production release. They allow many minor bug to be fixed and preparation of meta-data for a release.\n241: \n242: ## Development Conventions\n243: \n244: We highly appreciate external contributions to our package! We do request developers to adhere to the following conventions:\n245: \n246: - Issues\n247:   - Before working on any kind of development, please check existing issues to see whether there has been any\n248:     discussion and/or ongoing work on this topic.\n249:   - If no issue exists, please open one to allow discuss whether the development is desirable to the maintainers.\n250: - Branching\n251:   - Always branch from `dev` branch, unless there is the need to fix an undesired status of `main`. See above for more details about the branching workflow adopted.\n252:   - Our branch naming convention is: `<issue_number>_<description>_<author_name>`.\n253: - Pull Requests\n254:   - New developments must proceed via a pull request (PR) before they can be merged to either `main` or `dev` branches.\n255:   - When creating a pull request, please use the following naming convention: `<type>: <description>`. Example _types_\n256:     are `fix:`, `feat:`, `docs:`, and others based on the [Angular convention](https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/22b96b9/CONTRIBUTING.md#-commit-message-guidelines).\n257: \n258: ## Quality Control Workflows\n259: \n260: We have set up a number of [workflows](.github/workflows) that automatically check for some quality gateways when creating new PRs to `main` or\n261: `dev` branch, ensuring the long-term stability and maintainability of the package.\n262: \n263: ### [Build](.github/workflows/build.yml)\n264: \n265: This workflow tests whether the package can be built (i.e. pip installed) without errors.\n266: \n267: #### [Build-minimal](.github/workflows/build_minimal.yml)\n268: \n269: Checks that the package works without installing optional dependencies. If any optional dependency is needed throughout\n270: the code base or in any test, it should be conditionally imported, e.g. like this:\n271: \n272: ```py\n273: try:\n274:     from stable_baselines3.common.vec_env import DummyVecEnv\n275: \n276:     _SB3_AVAILABLE = True\n277: except ImportError:\n278:     _SB3_AVAILABLE = False\n279: ```\n280: \n281: ### [CFF Convert](.github/workflows/cffconvert.yml)\n282: \n283: This workflow checks whether the citation information can be read properly.\n284: \n285: ### [Docs Test](.github/workflows/docs-test.yml)\n286: \n287: This workflow checks whether the documentation can be built without errors.\n288: \n289: Note that this workflow does not publish the new documentation. Publishing new documentation is triggered automatically\n290: upon release as part of the release workflow, or can be done [manually](#publishing-the-docs).\n291: \n292: ### [Hyperlinks](.github/workflows/linkspector.yml)\n293: \n294: This workflow checks whether hyperlinks within the documentation are valid.\n295: \n296: ### [Linting](.github/workflows/linting.yml)\n297: \n298: This workflow checks whether the code adheres to our pre-set [linting and formatting\n299: conventions](#linting-and-formatting-python-files)\n300: \n301: ### [Notebooks](.github/workflows/notebooks.yml)\n302: \n303: This workflow checks whether all of the notebooks can run without triggering any errors.\n304: \n305: Note that this workflow actually runs each notebook one at a time, which can be a bit slow. Please keep the\n306: default values for e.g. epochs, training cycles, etc low so to speed this process up. Add a comment to users asking\n307: users to increase them if they actually want to the notebook productively.\n308: \n309: At the end of each run, there will be a log of how long each notebook took to test (this can also be done locally by\n310: running `pytest --nbmake docs --durations=0`). This can be used to check which\n311: notebook is slowing things down, to see if there's any way to improve that.\n312: \n313: ### [Code Quality](.github/workflows/sonarcloud.yml)\n314: \n315: This workflow does a number of checks on code quality, including test coverage.\n316: \n317: ### [Spell Check](.github/workflows/spell_check.yml)\n318: \n319: This workflow checks for typos throughout the code and associated files. If false positives appear, these can be added\n320: to the ignore list in [pyproject.toml](pyproject.toml) under `tool.typos`.\n321: \n322: ### [Static Typing](.github/workflows/static-typing.yml)\n323: \n324: This workflow checks that the [static typing](#static-typing) of the code base is correct.\n325: \n326: ## Making a Release\n327: \n328: Neurogym release versions follow the [semantic versioning convention](https://semver.org/). Creating a release involves creating a new branch where the Neurogym version is increased,followed by a new tag matching the new version. Once the tag is created, an action is triggered automatically to push the built wheel to PyPI. The individual steps are outlined below.\n329: \n330: ### Release Workflow\n331: \n332: 1. Make sure you have all required developers tools installed `pip install -e .'[test]'`. Prepare the codebase for the release (e.g., removing the unnecessary dev files, fix minor bugs if necessary). Do this by ensuring all tests pass `pytest -v` and that linting (`ruff check`) and formatting (`ruff format --check`) conventions are adhered to.\n333: \n334: 2. Create a release branch. We recommend that you choose a name for the branch that indicates the intent to make a release and the version (e.g. `release-2.3.4`). The *source* branch should be:\n335:     - The `dev` branch for traditional [release branches](https://nvie.com/posts/a-successful-git-branching-model/#release-branches).\n336:     - The `main` branch for [hotfix branches](https://nvie.com/posts/a-successful-git-branching-model/#hotfix-branches).\n337: \n338: 3. Decide on the [version level increase](#versioning), following [semantic versioning conventions](https://semver.org/). Use [bump-my-version](https://github.com/callowayproject/bump-my-version) to update the version throughout the package:\n339: \n340: ```sh\n341: bump-my-version bump <level> --commit --tag -vv\n342: ```\n343: \n344: It is noteworthy that PyPI automatically recognises the version within `pyproject.toml`, but there are some strict conventions that the version string must follow. Please read the [versioning specification](https://peps.python.org/pep-0440/).\n345: \n346: <span style=\"color:red;\">Important</span>: Note that the version string for PyPI ***does not have a leading `v`*** - it starts with a number. However, when creating the tag in the last step of this guide, please make sure that the version tag for the release starts with `v` followed by dot-separated numbers (e.g., `v2.3.4`). This will trigger the PyPI publishing workflow. Tags that do not match this pattern **will not trigger the PyPI publishing workflow**. This is a security measure against certain types of attacks based on tag tampering.\n347: \n348: 4. Create a PR for the new release branch targeting the `main` branch. When you create the PR, wait for all the checks to complete. If everything goes well, you can proceed to the next step. Ideally, there should be no issues since the only thing we are changing at this stage is the version. If the check step fails, the issues causing the failure should be fixed in the source branch before proceeding.\n349: \n350: 5. Merge the release branch into `main` and `dev`.\n351: \n352: 6. On the [Releases page](https://github.com/neurogym/neurogym/releases):\n353: \n354:    - Click `Draft a new release`\n355:    - Use `v<version number>` (e.g., `v2.3.4`) as both the release title and as a tag for the release (should match the version you selected above in step `3.`).\n356:    - Click `Generate release notes` to automatically load release notes from merged PRs since the last release.\n357:    - Adjust the notes as required.\n358:    - Ensure that `Set as latest release` is checked and that both other boxes are unchecked.\n359:    - Hit `Publish release`.\n360: \n361: This will automatically trigger a [GitHub workflow](https://github.com/neurogym/neurogym/actions/workflows/release.yml) that will take care of publishing the package on PyPi. You can open the [Neurogym PyPI page](https://pypi.org/manage/project/neurogym/releases/) to verify that the new release has been published.\n\n(End of file - total 361 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# `neurogym` developer documentation\n\nTable of Contents\n\n<!-- This table is automatically kept up to date using the \"Markdown All in One\" extension -->\n\n- [IDE Settings](#ide-settings)\n- [Package Setup](#package-setup)\n- [Running the Tests](#running-the-tests)\n  - [Test Coverage](#test-coverage)\n- [Style Conventions](#style-conventions)\n  - [Automated Style Adherence (for VScode users)](#automated-style-adherence-for-vscode-users)\n  - [Linting and Formatting (python files)](#linting-and-formatting-python-files)\n  - [Spell Check](#spell-check)\n  - [Docstrings](#docstrings)\n  - [Static Typing](#static-typing)\n  - [Formatting Non-python Files](#formatting-non-python-files)\n  - [Jupyter Notebooks](#jupyter-notebooks)\n- [User Documentation](#user-documentation)\n  - [Publishing the Docs](#publishing-the-docs)","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"README.dev.md","time":{"start":1775805097851,"end":1775805097857}}}]}
